# Leetcode

Solved the problem: https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-absolute-difference-between-elements-with-constraint/submissions/1959163595/

The outcome was really good with a runtime better than 82% of other users.

My solution uses two pointers at X distance afar and a set that allows search for the closest value in NlogN.

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    template<typename T>
    T find_closest(const std::set<T> &values, const T &target) {
        auto upper = values.lower_bound(target);

        if (upper == values.begin()) {
            return *upper;
        }

        if (upper == values.end()) {
            return *std::prev(upper);
        }

        auto lower = std::prev(upper);

        const T upper_value = *upper;
        const T lower_value = *lower;

        if (std::abs(upper_value - target) < std::abs(lower_value - target)) {
            return upper_value;
        }

        return lower_value;
    }

    int minAbsoluteDifference(std::vector<int> nums, int x) {
        std::set<int> S;
        int res = std::numeric_limits<int>::max();

        for (auto i = 0, j = x; j < static_cast<int>(nums.size()); j++, i++) {
            S.insert(nums[i]);
            // print_iters(S.begin(), S.end());

            auto closest = find_closest(S, nums[j]);
            auto diff = std::abs(nums[j] - closest);
            // std::cout << "closest to " << nums[j] << " is " << closest << " diff = " << diff << std::endl;

            res = std::min(res, diff);
        }

        return res;
    }
};
```
